
What is Code Quality?

Code Quality refers to how well-written, maintainable, reliable, efficient, secure, and readable the source code is. 
High-quality code is easier to understand, test, debug, and modify.

Characteristics of Good Code Quality
Readable – Easy to understand by other developers.
Maintainable – Easy to update or fix.
Reusable – Code can be reused in different parts of the application.
Efficient – Uses memory and CPU resources effectively.
Reliable – Produces correct results with fewer bugs.
Secure – Avoids vulnerabilities and security issues.
Testable – Easy to write unit and integration tests.
Example

❌ Poor Quality Code

public int c(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

✅ Good Quality Code

public int calculateTotalMarks(int mathMarks, int scienceMarks) {
    return mathMarks + scienceMarks;
}

The second example is more readable because of meaningful method and variable names.

What is SonarQube?

SonarQube is an open-source code quality and security analysis tool that continuously inspects source code for bugs, security vulnerabilities, code smells, and duplicated code.

It helps developers improve code quality before deploying applications.

Definition

SonarQube is a static code analysis tool that automatically analyzes source code to detect bugs, security vulnerabilities, code smells, and maintainability issues.

Features of SonarQube
    Static Code Analysis
    Detects Bugs
    Finds Security Vulnerabilities
    Detects Code Smells
    Measures Code Coverage
    Detects Duplicate Code
    Generates Quality Reports
    Supports Continuous Integration (CI/CD)
    Supports multiple languages like Java, Python, C#, JavaScript, C++, and more

What SonarQube Checks
    Bugs
      Null Pointer Exceptions
      Infinite loops
      Incorrect conditions
    Security Vulnerabilities
      SQL Injection
      Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
      Hardcoded passwords
    Code Smells
      Long methods
      Unused variables
      Duplicate logic
      High complexity
    Code Coverage
      Percentage of code covered by unit tests.
    Duplicated Code
      Identifies repeated code blocks.

SonarQube Metrics
    Reliability
    Security
    Maintainability
    Coverage
    Duplications
    Technical Debt

How SonarQube Works:

Developer writes code
          │
          ▼
Build Project (Maven/Gradle)
          │
          ▼
Sonar Scanner scans code
          │
          ▼
Results sent to SonarQube Server
          │
          ▼
Dashboard displays issues and reports

Advantages
    Improves code quality
    Detects bugs early
    Improves application security
    Enforces coding standards
    Reduces technical debt
    Integrates with Jenkins, GitHub, GitLab, Azure DevOps, etc.
    Provides detailed reports and dashboards


Example Maven Command

mvn clean verify sonar:sonar

This command:

  Builds the project
  Runs tests
  Sends the analysis report to SonarQube
